  Victoria doesn't know where Nathan is.

  She never does, but each time they have this conversation, she\'s a
  little softer. A little more raw, vulnerable. It only makes things
  harder.

  Max sees her with paint on her cashmere, with tape around her wrists.

  It\'s her fault Victoria ended up down there, that first time. Down in
  the Dark Room with #emph[him];, doomed to die scared and alone. It\'s
  all her fault, always her fault. She keeps getting people hurt. She
  keeps getting people #emph[killed];.

  If only Max hadn\'t opened her big mouth.

  \
  \

  Thrumming bass fades into gentle birdsong. As her eyes flutter open, Max
  becomes aware of two things.

  Her skull splitting headache has downgraded to a muted, omnipresent
  throb; and she\'s woken up in a thousand degree pile of limbs.

  She could have sworn she was back at that Vortex Club party. The neon
  lights, the booming speakers, the mixture of pity and disbelief in
  Victoria\'s eyes. Her ears are still ringing.

  Or maybe it #emph[was] just a dream. It\'s hard to tell the difference,
  sometimes.

  It's part of the reason why resting is so low on her list of priorities.
  As she's come to learn over the course of her many cycles, any form of
  unconsciousness is simply an excuse for her mind to drag her into a
  muddled labyrinth of moments past. She already has enough memories to
  parse through on a daily basis. Places, dates, times, the best answers
  to any given question, the quickest way to persuade someone. And the
  dreams --- flashbacks, nightmares, whatever you want to call them ---
  serve no greater purpose outside of jump-starting her into a delirious
  frenzy. She\'ll startle from one vision to find herself in another, and
  then another, repeating ad nauseam until she\'s never quite sure if
  anything she\'s doing is real or if she\'s just yet to wake up back at
  the beginning again.

  Then again, sometimes that part is a dream too.

  Thankfully, there\'s a blonde, flannel clad reality-check snoring away
  next to her. That alone makes the rest of her attempt to reorient
  herself far more effective than normal. It makes the whens and wheres
  easier, at least.

  A fresh cycle --- the last, with any luck --- somewhere in the vicinity
  of morning. She\'s still in Chloe\'s room, and however long she\'s been
  out, it\'s #emph[too] long.

  She pulls her arm out of the Rachel and Chloe sandwich it was trapped
  between, untangles her legs from theirs and worms her way out of all the
  blankets. Chloe gives a small noise of protest at all the movement, but
  ultimately just rolls over and nuzzles further into Rachel, who answers
  by sleepily slinging an arm over her back. They're all wrapped up in
  each other like a pair of koalas, impossibly close and entirely
  unwilling to let go. It would be cute if it weren\'t so heavily
  outweighed by the tarred, lingering thoughts of Chloe tipping over the
  cliff side, of Rachel\'s body in the junkyard.

  Max tears her gaze away, forces herself to stand.

  Now she needs to figure out the whats. What feels better, what still
  hurts. What she\'s already done and what she has to do next.

  Her joints are sort of creaky, sort of crunchy, and very unwilling to
  listen to her. Her neck in particular has a lot of complaints, of the
  searing and aching variety. The pain flares out in thin, angry tendrils
  along her upper back, and Max finds herself with a new and far more
  literal understanding of the phrase ‘death by a thousand cuts.' But it's
  fine. It's not stopping her from moving, so it isn't bad enough to worry
  about.

  She knows she got Chloe to hand over the warning letter, and that\'s at
  least some of the Atlas burden eased from her shoulders. She\'s come to
  appreciate David Madsen, in an odd, knight-in-rusted-armor sort of way.
  She still considers him deserving of the step-douche moniker, but he\'s
  there for her when it matters most. He always believes her, and he
  always comes to rescue her from the Dark Room. Plus he'll have much
  higher chances of convincing the police. She trusts that he\'ll handle
  Jefferson.

  That leaves her to handle everything else. Only problem being that
  \'everything else\' changed drastically the moment she rewound passed
  October. None of her insider knowledge or pinpoint predictions will be
  of much use for another few months, and still they may be worthless in
  the face of the alterations she's setting in motion. For the first time
  in ages, she has no idea what\'s coming. To top it all off, the storm is
  liable to rear its ugly head at any given moment, seeing as
  inconsistence is one of its few consistencies. It\'s all equal parts
  peculiar and terrifying.

  More terrifying, however, is facing her reflection.

  She looks… Well, to put it politely she looks like she\'s been backed
  over by Frank\'s RV. More than once. Also, her hair is a good few inches
  longer than it should be, which is not going to be easy to explain away.

  To put it less politely, she looks like a fucking drowned raccoon.

  The bags under her eyes are nothing new, they\'ve been there since the
  first days and have been the only thing to truly stay with her every
  time, but they certainly don\'t help the whole washed-up animal vibe she
  has going on. The results of her exponentially weakening appetite stare
  back at her in the form of sunken cheeks and a jawline more reminiscent
  of a switchblade. And of course, the aforementioned problem of her hair,
  bedraggled and scruffy and nothing resembling the semi-neat bob she\'d
  been wearing it in.

  No wonder Victoria's been going easy on her the last few rounds. She\'s
  a walking trainwreck and anyone could see it in a single glance.

  After splashing some water on her face and dutifully avoiding another
  glance in the mirror, Max decides her first order of business is to come
  up with a plausible explanation for herself. People are just going to
  keep asking, and the time limit for her parents\' frantic arrival in
  Arcadia Bay is probably already ticking down. Maybe she could string a
  few arrant details into a somewhat coherent story. Maybe she could
  convince her parents to just let her stay since she'll be enrolled in
  Blackwell come September anyhow.

  Is running off to live in the woods an option?

  Probably not. Not a smart one, anyways, but Max keeps the idea in her
  back pocket nonetheless.

  She stays out in the hallway for a bit, shambling from end to end under
  the notion that she does her best thinking when she\'s pacing, though
  she soon gains the courage to try and trot downstairs. On second
  thought, hubris might be a better word. Joyce was right, stairs are no
  good, no fun, very bad. Still, she pushes through it. Dizziness will
  fade. Pain will subside. She might not ever get another chance like
  this, so she has to make the best of it.

  There\'s a note left on the kitchen table, though judging from a quick
  skim of its contents it wasn\'t meant for her. The bottle of
  acetaminophen and the candy bar sitting next to it, on the other hand.
  It\'s sweet of Joyce to remember her favorite junk food after all these
  years, but Max passes over it in favor of dry-swallowing two pills. She
  doubts they\'ll do much to aid a chronic, time-travel induced migraine,
  but it\'s worth a shot.

  She just needs to clear her head and get started on a plan. Get back up
  and get running. She had a dream last night about being told that she
  could slow down, and she knows it must have been a dream because such
  foolish optimism could only be the product of fantasy. The longer she
  stays still, the less she\'ll want to move, and she can\'t stop. Even if
  she wants to.

  She doesn't get very far in her plotting on account of the fact that
  fate has other ideas for her.

  First comes the muffled shout of, \"Dude, get #emph[up];, c\'mon.\"

  Quickly followed by the sound of Chloe\'s bedroom door crashing open.

  \"Jesus, what time is it?\"

  \"Max? Max, where\'d you go?\"

  And she tries to call out an answer, but her stupid voice still refuses
  to come out at anything above a murmur and she can picture the way Chloe
  is about to rush down the stairs, trip and sprain her ankle or
  something. Probably because it happened once before when they were
  younger. Between that and her tendency to do things without thinking
  whenever she hears Chloe talking in that frantic, distressed tone, Max
  rewinds without hesitation.

  It\'s still a fraction of what it used to be, but she can\'t help the
  spark of excitement when she manages to turn back a far more substantial
  amount of time than her last attempt. She might just lose it altogether
  if her powers don\'t fully recover. Somehow they are both the reason
  she's unravelling and the final thread she clings to.

  Maybe she moves a bit too fast but she makes it to the bottom of the
  stairs as the door slams open again, just in time to see Chloe stumbling
  into the hall with a decidedly groggy Rachel trailing behind her.
  They\'ve both got bedhead to rival her own, and it looks like they fell
  asleep in whatever they\'d been wearing yesterday.

  \"Jesus, what time is it?\"

  \"Max? Max, where\'d you--\"

  \"Hi,\" Max waves up at them, holding back a wince at the pitiful sound
  of her greeting.

  Rachel squints down at her like she\'s trying to figure out a calculus
  equation and Chloe heaves a sigh, running a hand through her bangs.

  \"Fuck, you scared the shit outta me, man. Are you okay? What are you
  doing down there?\"

  Alarm bells sound off. More questions to duck and weave her way around.
  Max isn\'t sure if this whole situation has made her better or worse at
  thinking on the spot, but she does know that lying to and/or hiding
  things from Chloe is never easy. Even if it's safer that way, even if
  it's necessary, and evidently even when put in a position that literally
  prevents her from saying too much, very rarely does she find it in
  herself to follow through with the dishonesty.

  “M'fine. Wanted to get moving.” A coherent sentence, at least.

  Chloe opens and closes her mouth a few times as if struggling to process
  the words.

  Rachel makes an expression of complete and utter bemusement. “You're
  fucking nuts,” she says to Max, before turning to Chloe and gesturing
  down the stairs in a huff. “Chloe, she's fucking nuts.”

  “#emph[Rachel];,” Chloe whisper-shouts, elbowing her in the side

  “What? Can you tell me I'm wrong?” Rachel elbows her back. “If I were
  her I'd be in bed the whole damn week.”

  “Dude, be nice.”

  \"This #emph[is] nice for hungover me and you know it.\"

  Max lets out a laugh, small and half choked, but a laugh nonetheless.
  They bicker like Joyce and William used to. Just with a lot more cussing
  and gratuitous use of the word, \'dude.\'

  Max remembers finding the picture of Rachel in Chloe\'s room, how she\'d
  scrambled to take it, to hold it close. The shirts hung up beside hers
  in the closet. The writing on the wall in the junkyard shack. The way
  Chloe\'s eyes softened as she said, \"#emph[She was my angel];.\"

  \"What\'s so funny?\" they both splutter, just the slightest bit
  off-time, before eyeing each other and devolving into their own distinct
  flavors of flustered.

  And oh, what rib shaking elation rattles through her at the sight of it.
  Liquid sunlight shot straight through her veins, strawberry lightning
  fizzling through each strained, twitching muscle of her heart. Happiness
  is foreign to her at this point, and therefore just as likely to cloud
  her judgement as carnal anxiety or blind anguish.

  She rewinds so she can see it again.

  And again. And then she holds a preemptive sleeve over her nose and
  says, \"Nothing.\"

  #emph[Just happy to see you] stays stuck in her throat.

  Common sense taps her on the shoulder and reminds her that she\'s still
  wearing one of Rachel\'s sweaters and probably shouldn\'t be so careless
  with it. Not to mention she really doesn\'t want either of them to see
  or deal with this more than they've already had to. She can take care of
  it herself. So she slips back to the kitchen without another word,
  wrestles her way out of the sweater and grabs a fistful of paper towel.

  What was it Joyce had told her to do? Lean forward and pinch her
  nostrils shut?

  They find her half bent over the sink, and though she doesn\'t turn to
  see them Max points in what she thinks is the direction of the discarded
  item of clothing and mutters, \"Sorry if I got blood on it.\" Which was
  a mistake, because her headache spikes and she can feel the blood
  trickling down over her mouth and boy does she miss when this bullshit
  wasn\'t a part of her day to day routine.

  For a minute, no one says anything.

  Then, Chloe scoffs. \"Max, you\'re fucking nuts. Who cares about the
  sweater, it\'s in better shape than you are. Should I--\"

  \"S\'fine,\" Max mutters, against her better judgement. \"It\'ll… stop…
  in a minute.\"

  Each pause is accented by a dripping sound. It would almost be comical
  if it weren't for, well, everything about it. She's going to have to get
  better at rationing both her words and her rewinds.

  “You say that like this is a regular thing for you.”

  Rachel's voice is deeper than Max thought it would be, and she doesn't
  know if she'll ever quite get used to it. In a good way, of course.
  Sweet, mellifluous honey, a distinct air of certainty dipped in
  softness. Nothing her imagination came up with could compare to actually
  hearing it, and when Max cleans herself off and actually faces her, it's
  like staring into the blinding core of a star. The already loose thought
  of curbing her answers burns up in the light.

  “Kinda.”

  This earns a raised eyebrow from Chloe, though her subsequent
  incredulous query of, \"Since when?\" is interrupted by Rachel handing
  her the note from the table.

  She's no less blinding to look at. There's the simmering relief of
  seeing her alive and well again, but there's also a veritable cocktail
  of grief, longing, guilt and adoration that roils in Max's chest each
  time their eyes meet. She feels simultaneously sick and cured, lost and
  found. It all swells to a scalding, saccharine crescendo, and the joy of
  being by her side wins out over everything else like it does every time.

  Maybe she #emph[could] stop. Just for a second. Just to look at them a
  little more.

  Because what has she been working for, what has she been suffering for,
  what has she torn herself apart for if not to see them live?

  “Yo, earth to Max.” She blinks, and finds Chloe has gotten close enough
  to lay a hand on her arm. \"You need to sit down or something? You\'re
  spacing out hardcore.\"

  #emph[Just for a second];, Max tells herself.

  Classes are cancelled for the day, according to the note Joyce left, and
  Max tries to not to show the full depth of her solace. She merely nods
  along to the offer of food and basks in the weight of their presence.
  She has to enjoy these moments of relative peace while she has them.
  They're part of what makes the struggle so worthwhile.

  It turns out Rachel is one of those ‘don't talk to me until I've had my
  coffee' types. She keeps that grumpy slouch in her posture until she's
  halfway through the cup, after which she brightens considerably and
  offers her gratitude with a satisfied grin. Chloe smiles too, and god is
  it a sight for sore eyes.

  “Ah, there she is,” she chuckles, reaching over to ruffle Rachel's hair,
  eyes lit soft and warm with mirth.

  “I never left, you dweeb,” Rachel answers, playfully swatting the girl's
  hand away.

  Max has to be careful, or she\'ll be tempted to stop and stare forever.

