  for giving the girl her first cigarette?

  Other than that she\'s doing a better job keeping her cool than Rachel,
  which is ass backwards and more than a little concerning. But she isn\'t
  sure how to bring it up without letting on to the aforementioned problem
  of her lost marbles, on account of the hushed, horrific conversation she
  had with step-douche last night in the hall.

  For once, he was forthcoming, and for once, Chloe was almost sort of
  grateful for his lack of boundaries.

  He said that everything in Max\'s note was accurate, and then proceeded
  to divulge half its contents. The location, the setup, the assortment of
  vials and syringes, the shelf full of neatly arranged \'photo albums\'
  hand labeled with the name of each girl found within. Every little
  thing, down to the chilling detail that there would be no evidence of
  her being there, was true. Including the part about the freak behind it
  all having eyes for Rachel. And that sure elicited some genuine,
  seething disgust, but then he told her about the empty album with
  Rachel\'s name on it, and #emph[that] created the odd marriage of stone
  cold fear and boiling rage that she\'s currently muddled in.

  Oh, and the freak in question is one of their fucking teachers.

  Really, how is she supposed to cope with the knowledge that Rachel was
  inches from someone so dangerous practically every day? Or the idea that
  Max spent enough time in this dude\'s murder basement that she could
  commit so many details to memory? Or the fact that she herself has
  walked right past him on several occasions without sparing a second
  glance?

  Somehow, she\'s managing. Or at least managing to keep herself balanced
  between two high density emotions to the point of void-like equilibrium.
  That counts as being calm, right? It's gonna have to for now, because if
  the scales tip in either direction she can't guarantee she won't just
  default to blowing up at the first person who speaks to her. And she
  can't imagine either Rachel or Max are in the market to be on the losing
  end of her temper.

  So keeps herself taut and rigid and vehemently steers herself away from
  the darker thoughts. She doesn't show her disappointment when Rachel
  mutters about James wanting her home after the fifth ignored call in a
  half-hour span --- of course he already knows, and with her rampant
  curiosity surely Rachel will too by the end of the night --- even if it
  takes what little wind had been in her sails. She keeps her what the
  hell's and why the hell's under trembling lock and key, no matter how
  they keep piling up. She holds the white-water crush of panic at bay,
  despite the force of the tidal wave.

  But then, it appears. The final straw.

  After Rachel's grumbling and reluctant departure, Max had been fidgeting
  with her hair. Chloe had offered to grab her something to wear while she
  hopped in the shower. All well and good, normal as can be for the
  situation they're in. The problem arises from two key factors. First,
  Max's ruffled mane has gone limp from the water, no longer so obscuring
  as it had been. Second, due to their height difference, all of Chloe's
  shirts are super loose on Max, especially around the collar. So when she
  shuffles out in that egregiously baggy Fire Walk t-shirt and Chloe
  catches a glimpse of her from the back, the sag of the fabric and the
  part of hair reveals a monstrous patch of scarring trailing down Max's
  neck.

  “Max,” she chokes out, “What the fuck is that?”

  She's moving before she can think it through, coming up behind the girl
  and reaching to tug the shirt collar aside. A myriad of reddened
  indentations greet her, stark against Max's pale skin and billowing into
  a great latticework of marring. It almost looks like lightning,
  branching out thinner and thinner with every splicing strike, all
  stemming from a single blotch of a scar scorched into the nape of her
  neck.

  As previously stated: What. The. Fuck.

  Max flinches away from her. “Fell. Probably.”

  Chloe can practically feel the rationality leaving her, instantaneous
  and reverberating like a guitar string snapping mid-pluck. “Dude, I know
  you can't see it, but there's no fucking way you got this from falling.
  When the hell did this happen?”

  “Dunno.”

  “Is there anything you do know?” Chloe winces at her harsh tone, but now
  that she\'s lost her grip there\'s nothing she can do to stop the words
  from spilling out. “Cause I've been trying to figure out what to fucking
  #emph[do] about all of this and I just-- I need you to #emph[tell me];,
  Max. Something, anything. Please.”

  There's a moment's silence wherein Max winds tense, wrapping her arms
  around herself. Chloe watches the way she digs her nails into her arms.
  “Can't.”

  “Why the fuck not?”

  “...Wouldn't believe me.”

  “Like hell I wouldn't,\" she snaps, because she never once thought about
  how monumentally it would suck to know Max felt that way. \"Try me.\"

  By the look of that thing she could say she was mauled by a t-rex and
  Chloe would believe it no question. She just needs to know what the fuck
  is going on so she can figure out how to help.

  But Max just shakes her head, her voice cracking under its own weight
  when she says, \"Don\'t want you to get hurt.\"

  And that\'s even harder to swallow, considering she\'s the one who came
  limping back into Chloe\'s life looking more like roadkill than the
  goofy kid she\'d last been. But she was always the type to worry about
  others first. There was one instance back in the day where they\'d
  gotten a little too rambunctious in their gallivanting and taken a bit
  of a tumble, and Chloe can still remember the way Max had gotten up
  first, scrambled to her side and held out a scraped, bruising hand to
  help her back to her feet.

  \"I won\'t.\" Chloe lets out a sigh, wills the adrenaline to melt. It
  stays unfortunately solid. \"Step-douche said they\'re gonna put that
  guy away. He won\'t hurt anyone anymore.\"

  She hates the way Max cringes at the mere allusion.

  Another frantic shake of her head. \"Not just him. Me.\"

  All things considered, it isn\'t very loud, but it\'s the most volume
  she\'s managed as of recent, and that\'s enough to make Chloe jump.

  Max finally turns to show her glassy, faraway gaze. \"I get
  #emph[everyone] hurt.\" Her breath comes quick and shallow, and blood
  begins to drip from her nose as she adds a bitter, breaking, \"I always
  do. I always do.\"

  \"Shit, Max, You\'re--\"

  \"Don\'t. It's-- It\'s okay. M\'sorry.\" She rushes to cover herself up,
  takes a few timid steps away. Then, a hissed aside, \"You\'re doing it
  again. Bad Max. Can\'t you get anything right?\"

  Okay. Okay okay okay, crisis mode activated.

  \"Hey.\" Chloe stops her before she can apologize again. If you\'d asked
  her a week ago she would have wanted an apology, but now each one she
  hears is more akin to swallowing glass. “Dude, slow down.”

  “I #emph[can't];,” Max croaks, eyes wide and wild and dire in a way that
  sends uncanny sparks of deja-vu prickling through Chloe\'s veins. “If I
  slow down I'll lose you again n' I can't-- can't fix anything like this,
  I can't, so I won't lose you again, gotta keep going so I don't lose
  you--”

  Chloe does the only thing she can think to do. She closes their
  distance, takes Max's face in both hands --- gently, so goddamn gently,
  more gentle than she's ever been in her entire life --- tilts it up and
  tries her best not to focus on the blood. “#emph[Max];. Max, look at me.
  I'm right here, you aren't gonna lose me.”

  \"But--\"

  \"No buts.\" She tightens her grip, half-consciously strokes a thumb
  over her cheek. \"I\'m fine, see? I don\'t know where your head is
  taking you, but you gotta come back.\"

  Max looks up at her, sombre and knowing, heavy and hopeless, before
  relenting with a choked little whimper. She shuts her eyes, lets slip a
  few silent tears, leans into Chloe\'s hand and fights her way through an
  exhale.

  And god, she seems even smaller like this.

  Small, brittle, and long since shattered.

  \"Still with me?\" A weak nod. \"Good. C\'mon, let\'s get your nose
  taken care of.\"

  Though Chloe has to practically drag her back to the bathroom sink, once
  they get there she\'s quick to regain her earlier reluctance and insists
  on doing everything herself. Even with her hands shaking. She stays
  doubled over with all of her weight held on one arm in spite of the way
  it visibly protests the strain, and Chloe finds herself taking the
  opportunity to try and look at that-- that #emph[thing];, whatever it
  is.

  It sort of reminds her of a lichtenberg figure, but she\'s almost
  positive that they don\'t stick around very long. Nor do they look so
  much like carved trails through the skin. She tries to imagine what
  could have caused it, what it must have felt like, visceral unease
  growing with each centimeter she takes in. She hasn\'t even seen it in
  full. She doesn\'t know if she wants to.

  The question comes cautious, hushed, and guilty. \"Does it hurt?\"

  Max goes stock still. Chloe can see the debate swirling in her eyes
  through the mirror. \"...A little.\"

  \"What can I do?\"

  Chloe isn\'t sure what she\'s expecting, maybe a refusal, maybe a shrug,
  maybe no answer at all. What she gets is confessional and dim. What she
  gets is burdened beyond comprehension.

  What she gets is muted conviction.

  \"Tell me I can do this,\" Max whispers, watching diluted crimson wash
  down the drain. \"Tell me I won\'t fuck it up.\"

  #emph[Fuck what up] ? Chloe wants to ask, because every word out of the
  girl\'s mouth is making less and less sense, and the levels of concern
  have gone from frankly insane to downright astronomical in proportion.
  Instead, she falls back on tried and true reassurance from their younger
  days, familiar words bubbling up from somewhere far brighter than here
  and now.

  \"You got this, Max. You\'ll figure it out. You always do.\"

  True, it usually came about in relation to math homework or some other
  mundanity, but recognition shows itself in the slow deflation of her
  posture. For a moment she seems like she\'s calmed down.

  It doesn\'t last as long as it should.

  She sort of squares herself up, fumbles through finishing cleaning off
  her face and does not startle the same way Chloe does at the sound of
  the front door opening downstairs, the voice calling out to them from
  below.

  \"Girls? I\'m back.\"

  Shit. Is it that late already?

  She looks at Max as if to ask, #emph[are you up for this?] Max gives her
  a nod in return, eyes half steeled and half corroded.

  \"In here, mom,\" Chloe calls out as she opens the door, and her mother
  is already in the process of rushing up the stairs to greet them.

  \"Max, honey, how are you feeling? I\'ve got your mother on the phone,
  she really wants to talk to you.\"

  It feels a little weird to argue against that, but after what she just
  caused and witnessed Chloe isn\'t sure a lengthy conversation of any
  kind is a good idea, no matter the other participant. \"I don\'t know,\"
  she starts to say, only to be halted by a small tug on her sleeve.

  \"S\'okay,\" Max assures, in that same stiff, resigned tone. Chloe
  doesn\'t miss the shudder that rolls through her thin frame as she takes
  the phone from Joyce\'s hand. For someone who's been through some
  unspeakably whack-ass traumatic shit and wound up far from home, she
  really doesn't look happy to hear from her parents.

  Chloe was fully prepared to follow alongside her, were it not for the
  disapproving look sent her way.

  \"Give them a minute,\" her mother says in a murmur, tone weary and
  warning.

  So she winds up waiting outside her room, leaned up against the wall
  with her arms crossed and mind running a thousand miles a minute. She\'s
  not trying to eavesdrop or anything, she just can\'t shake the worry
  that if Max starts panicking again she'll lose half her blood content
  and they\'ll finally have to give in and send her off in an ambulance.
  Still, she can\'t help but overhear the odd word. As the minutes tick by
  in fitful, agonizing anticipation, an odd word turns into several;
  steadily growing in raspy volume. Several turns into something Chloe
  thought impossible, and as it dawns on her what\'s going on she almost
  can\'t believe what she\'s hearing.

  Max is arguing with her mom.

  They're fucking #emph[arguing];.

  Each sentence she catches is half a growl, raw and scratchy, brimming
  with frustration so thoroughly unlike anything she's ever heard from
  Max's mouth. Underneath it all lurks the unmistakable lilt of bone-deep
  exhaustion.

  \"Doesn\'t matter.\"

  \"I can look after myself.\"

  \"Can\'t make me.\"

  \"I-- I don\'t fucking #emph[care];. M\'not going.\"

  And holy shit, she did not just drop an f-bomb on her mom. That\'s like,
  the third law of the universe. Conservation of mass, equal and opposite
  reactions, don\'t curse in front of Vanessa Caulfield if you want to
  live. In fact, Chloe is so floored by this that she doesn\'t clue in to
  the ensuing scuffling, the sound of paper tearing, the grating slide of
  vinyl and wood that she ought to know all too well.

  Not until it\'s too late. Not until it\'s gone quiet.

  \"Max?\"

  No answer. Acrid, gnawing dread takes hold of her.

  \"Max, dude, are you--\"

  Her room is empty.

  The phone sits alone on the bed.

  A chilled evening breeze worms its way through the half open window,
  rustling the scrap of paper on the floor beneath it. The notebook it
  originated from lays discarded at its side, along with an uncapped pen.

  In a hasty, shaking facsimile of Max\'s handwriting: #emph[I had to.
  Please stay out of trouble while I\'m gone.]
